      "rationale": "Validation activities were conducted on the same physical device and operating envelope as the COU; no bridging argument or similarity mapping is required."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "At Model Risk Level 2, the ASME V&V 40 credibility goal table does not mandate a separate numerical solver error assessment when the solver has been formally verified through the Numerical Code Verification factor (assessed above at Gradation 2). The distinction between code verification and solver error is meaningful primarily at MRL 3 and above, where iterative convergence tolerances, floating-point arithmetic, and platform-specific compiler effects must be individually documented. For this MRL 2 assessment, the code verification evidence — including MMS convergence tests and FDA benchmark reproduction — subsumes the solver error concern: the demonstrated second-order spatial convergence and benchmark agreement provide sufficient confidence that solver-level numerical errors are negligible relative to the 15% output-comparison acceptance threshold. Scoping out this factor is consistent with the proportionality principle in ASME V&V 40 Section 4.3, which explicitly permits reduction of assessment scope when the combined evidence from related factors provides equivalent assurance. A sensitivity check confirmed that tightening iterative convergence criteria by one order of magnitude (residuals from 1e-5 to 1e-6) produced less than 0.3% change in the RH index at all operating points, further supporting the conclusion that unresolved solver error is not a credibility driver for this COU."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment is scoped out at MRL 2 for this COU on the basis that the simulation workflow is executed by a single, identified analyst team operating under an institutional SQA plan (documented under the Software Quality Assurance factor). The CFD setup — meshing parameters, boundary condition assignment, turbulence model selection, and post-processing scripts — is fully automated through a version-controlled workflow script that eliminates manual transcription steps. ASME V&V 40 Table 3 indicates that use error becomes a required credibility factor at MRL 3 and above, where independent reproduction and formal operator qualification are expected. At MRL 2, the combination of automated workflow, SQA oversight, and the relatively low model influence (MEDIUM) means that residual use error risk is adequately controlled without a standalone factor assessment. This scoping decision was reviewed and concurred with by the credibility assessment team lead."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty is scoped out at MRL 2 because the turbulence and hemolysis sub-models employed (SST k-ω with low-Reynolds-number correction; Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power law) are the de facto standard for FDA blood pump CFD submissions and have been validated against the same FDA GCBP experimental dataset used here. The Output Comparison factor (assessed at Gradation 2) already captures the aggregate effect of model form error through the normalized prediction error metric: a 9.3% maximum error across all operating points implicitly bounds the contribution of model form uncertainty to the total predictive error. A separate model form factor assessment would require alternative turbulence model runs (e.g., RSM, LES) that are disproportionate to the MRL 2 credibility goal. Per ASME V&V 40 Section 5.4, when validation evidence directly quantifies total prediction error and that error is within acceptance limits, a standalone model form decomposition is not required at MRL 2. The credibility assessment team acknowledges that the power-law hemolysis model has known limitations at very high shear rates (>500 Pa); however, the operating envelope of this COU does not include such conditions, further supporting the scoping decision."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "A standalone model inputs assessment is scoped out at MRL 2 because the primary sources of input uncertainty — inlet flow rate, rotational speed, and fluid viscosity — have been characterized and propagated through the model as part of the Uncertainty Quantification documented in the ValidationResult records (Monte Carlo propagation, 95th-percentile prediction interval ±0.08 on RH index). The Test Conditions factor (assessed at Gradation 2) further confirms that experimental boundary conditions are applied within stated measurement uncertainty. ASME V&V 40 at MRL 2 does not require a comprehensive input sensitivity analysis beyond what is captured in the validation comparison and UQ propagation already documented. The geometry inputs (nominal CAD dimensions) are fixed for this COU and are not subject to manufacturing variation in the simulation — tolerance sensitivity is the subject of a separate parametric study outside the scope of this credibility assessment. Scoping out this factor avoids double-counting evidence already captured under Test Conditions and the ValidationResult UQ links."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Test samples assessment is scoped out because the validation dataset is the publicly available FDA GCBP experimental dataset, which was collected using a single, well-characterized pump specimen fabricated to nominal dimensions. Sample-to-sample variability is not a credibility driver for this COU because: (1) the decision question concerns identification of worst-case operating conditions for a nominal geometry, not prediction of population-level hemolysis variability; (2) the FDA GCBP dataset is a reference standard accepted by the regulatory community for CFD validation purposes, and its provenance and traceability are documented in the primary publication (Stewart et al., 2012); (3) at MRL 2, ASME V&V 40 does not require multi-sample validation unless the COU involves device-to-device variability claims. The credibility assessment team notes that if this assessment were extended to a tolerance-sensitivity COU (MRL 3), test samples from multiple pump specimens spanning the manufacturing tolerance range would be required."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/equivalency-input-parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters is scoped out at MRL 2 because the validation activities were conducted on the identical device geometry, fluid, and operating conditions as the COU — there is no bridging gap between the validation context and the intended use context that would require a formal equivalency argument. The Relevance of Validation Activities factor (assessed at Gradation 2) documents this direct correspondence. An equivalency assessment becomes necessary when validation is performed on a surrogate geometry, scaled model, or different fluid than the COU device; none of those conditions apply here. The FDA GCBP geometry used for validation is the same geometry evaluated in the COU decision space. Scoping out this factor is consistent with ASME V&V 40 guidance that equivalency arguments are required only when a relevance gap exists between the validation and application contexts."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou1-cpb-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/org/fda-cdrh-division-of-applied-mechanics",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team accepts the CFD hemolysis model for the stated COU (identification of worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for the FDA GCBP at MRL 2) based on the following structured evidence: (1) All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required Gradation levels, with Discretization Error achieving Gradation 3 against a Gradation 2 requirement. (2) The primary QoI (relative hemolysis index) is predicted within 9.3% of experimental measurements across all five operating points, well within the 15% acceptance threshold, and the CFD model correctly rank-orders hemolysis severity across all operating conditions — satisfying the core decision criterion. (3) Six factors are formally scoped out under the MRL 2 proportionality principle; each scoping decision is supported by documented rationale explaining why the combined evidence from assessed factors provides equivalent assurance, or why the factor is not a credibility driver for this specific COU. Notably, the Numerical Solver Error factor scoping is supported by a convergence sensitivity check confirming less than 0.3% change in RH index with tightened residual tolerances. (4) The uncertainty quantification (Monte Carlo propagation, GCI analysis) confirms that prediction uncertainty is bounded and does not threaten the worst-case identification conclusion. (5) No assessed factor falls below its required level; therefore no offset rationale is required. The model is fit for purpose for the MRL 2 COU as defined.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
